            <div class="content-section" style="margin-top: 20px;">
                <h3>Additional Laboratory Findings</h3>
                <div class="two-column">
                    <div>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Troponin:</strong> 27 → 31 → 32 (stable)</li>
                            <li><strong>BNP:</strong> 3,743 (markedly elevated)</li>
                            <li><strong>Procalcitonin:</strong> 0.07 (very low)</li>
                            <li><strong>CRP:</strong> 3.21 (mildly elevated)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Influenza A/B:</strong> Negative</li>
                            <li><strong>RSV:</strong> Negative</li>
                            <li><strong>COVID-19:</strong> Negative</li>
                            <li><strong>Blood cultures:</strong> Pending</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top: 20px;">
                <p><strong>Pattern Recognition:</strong> Persistent leukocytosis, chronic anemia ("baseline"), 
                very low procalcitonin. What does this constellation suggest?</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 6: Initial Imaging -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Imaging Studies</h1>
            
            <div class="timeline">
                <div class="timeline-item">
                    <div class="timeline-date">Initial Admission Chest X-Ray</div>
                    <p><strong>Finding:</strong> No acute cardiopulmonary changes</p>
                    <p><em>Patient admitted for observation</em></p>
                </div>

                <div class="timeline-item">
                    <div class="timeline-date">Day 7 Chest X-Ray</div>
                    <p><strong>Finding:</strong> Patchy non-consolidated right lower lobe airspace opacities</p>
                    <p><strong>Impression:</strong> Concerning for pneumonia</p>
                    <p><em>Prompted antibiotics and further workup</em></p>
                </div>

                <div class="timeline-item">
                    <div class="timeline-date">CT Head (without contrast)</div>
                    <p><strong>Finding:</strong> No acute intracranial process or hemorrhage</p>
                    <p><em>Obtained for altered mental status evaluation</em></p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="content-section" style="margin-top: 30px;">
                <h3>ECG Findings</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Sinus rhythm, rate 63 bpm</li>
                    <li>T wave inversions in lead III</li>
                    <li>No ST elevations or depressions</li>
                    <li>QTc: 439 ms (normal)</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="success-box">
                <p><strong>Initial Antibiotic:</strong> Ceftriaxone 1g IV given at outside hospital</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 7: Differential Diagnosis -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Interactive Pause: Differential Diagnosis</h1>
            
            <div class="highlight-box">
                <h2 style="color: var(--warning-color); margin-top: 0;">Clinical Reasoning Exercise</h2>
                <p style="font-size: 1.2em; margin: 15px 0;">
                    Let's pause and consider what we know so far...
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content-section">
                <h3>Clinical Presentation</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>82-year-old with recurrent altered mental status and hypoxic respiratory failure</li>
                    <li>Left hospital AMA 2 days ago, now returning worse</li>
                    <li>Initial hypotension (65/45), now stabilized</li>
                    <li>Persistent hypoxemia (84% → 96% on 4L O2)</li>
                    <li>Progressive dementia with medication non-compliance</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="content-section">
                <h3>Laboratory Highlights</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Leukocytosis (WBC 13.61)</li>
                    <li>Anemia (Hgb 10.8) documented as "baseline"</li>
                    <li>Stage 4 CKD (Cr 2.60, eGFR 24)</li>
                    <li>Elevated but stable troponin</li>
                    <li><strong>Markedly elevated BNP (3,743)</strong></li>
                    <li><strong>Very low procalcitonin (0.07)</strong></li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="learning-point">
                <h3>What's on YOUR Differential?</h3>
                <p>Consider these categories:</p>
                <ol>
                    <li><strong>Infectious:</strong> CAP, aspiration, healthcare-associated, atypical</li>
                    <li><strong>Cardiac:</strong> Acute decompensated heart failure, demand ischemia</li>
                    <li><strong>Medication/Toxicity:</strong> Non-compliance, over-sedation</li>
                    <li><strong>Neurologic:</strong> Progression of dementia, CVA, delirium</li>
                    <li><strong>Renal/Metabolic:</strong> Uremia, metabolic encephalopathy</li>
                    <li><strong>Social:</strong> Unsafe discharge, inadequate support</li>
                </ol>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 8: The Pivotal CT -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>The Pivotal CT Scan</h1>
            
            <div class="content-section">
                <h3>CTA Chest with IV Contrast (PE Protocol)</h3>
                <p><strong>Indication:</strong> Hypoxia, shortness of breath, rule out pulmonary embolism</p>
            </div>

            <div class="success-box">
                <h3>Finding #1: Pulmonary Vasculature</h3>
                <p><span class="checkmark">✓</span> <strong>No acute pulmonary embolism</strong></p>
            </div>

            <div class="content-section">
                <h3>Finding #2: Pulmonary Parenchyma</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Area of consolidation within the right lower lobe</li>
                    <li>Scattered areas of ground-glass opacity (bilateral)</li>
                    <li>Pattern suggestive of pneumonia</li>
                    <li>Possible additional areas of aspiration</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="critical-box">
                <h3>Finding #3: The Critical Observation</h3>
                <blockquote style="font-size: 1.2em; border-left-color: var(--accent-color); background: white;">
                    "Constellation of findings suggestive of <strong>lymphomatous disorder</strong> with 
                    multiple areas of <strong>lymphadenopathy</strong> in the chest and visualized upper abdomen"
                </blockquote>
                
                <h4 style="margin-top: 20px;">Lymphadenopathy Locations:</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li>Axillary (bilateral)</li>
                    <li>Mediastinal (multiple stations)</li>
                    <li>Hilar (bilateral)</li>
                    <li>Retroperitoneal</li>
                    <li>Porta hepatis</li>
                </ul>
                
                <p style="margin-top: 20px; font-size: 1.2em; font-weight: bold;">
                    Pattern: <span class="lab-high">GENERALIZED LYMPHADENOPATHY</span> (≥2 non-contiguous regions)
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="emphasis">
                The radiologist is telling us this patient has a lymphoproliferative disorder.
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 9: Admission Assessment -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Admission Assessment & Plan</h1>
            
            <div class="content-section">
                <h3>Problem List Documented</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li>Acute Hypoxic Respiratory Failure / CAP / Acute Encephalopathy</li>
                    <li>Elevated Troponin</li>
                    <li><strong>"Abnormal CT Scan"</strong></li>
                    <li>CKD Stage 3 → AKI</li>
                    <li>Vascular Dementia</li>
                    <li>Hypertension, Hyperlipidemia, GERD</li>
                    <li>Mood Disorder, Myasthenia Gravis, Peripheral Neuropathy</li>
                    <li>Restless Legs Syndrome, BPH</li>
                </ol>
            </div>

            <div class="content-section">
                <h3>Plan for "Abnormal CT Scan"</h3>
                <blockquote>
                    "In addition to possible pneumonia on CT chest also <strong>multiple areas of 
                    lymphadenopathy in chest and visualized upper abdomen</strong>"
                    <br><br>
                    "<strong>Consider CT abdomen</strong> to rule out further areas of lymphadenopathy 
                    and other noninfectious processes after resolution of acute infection."
                </blockquote>
            </div>

            <div class="highlight-box">
                <h3>Clinical Interpretation</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Lymphadenopathy treated as <strong>new finding</strong></li>
                    <li>Planning additional diagnostic workup (CT abdomen)</li>
                    <li>Likely considering lymph node biopsy</li>
                    <li>No immediate hematology consultation mentioned</li>
                    <li>No recognition of immunocompromised status</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="success-box">
                <h3>Treatment Plan</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Continue ceftriaxone, add azithromycin</li>
                    <li>Wean oxygen as tolerated</li>
                    <li>Echocardiogram in morning (for elevated BNP/troponin)</li>
                    <li>Monitor clinical status</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 10: What Was Actually in the Chart - Part 1 -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Learning Opportunity: Chart Review Reveals Important History</h1>
            
            <div class="critical-box">
                <h2 style="margin-top: 0;">Hematology/Oncology Note - 3 Months Prior</h2>
                <p style="font-size: 1.2em;">
                    A comprehensive note from <strong>August 2025</strong> (11 weeks before admission) 
                    was present in the electronic medical record.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="content-section">
                <h3>Key Information from Hematology Note</h3>
                
                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4>Established Diagnosis</h4>
                    <p style="font-size: 1.3em; font-weight: bold; color: var(--accent-color);">
                        Small Lymphocytic Lymphoma/Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia (SLL/CLL)
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Diagnosis Date:</strong> July 2024 (16 months prior)</li>
                        <li><strong>Stage:</strong> Lugano Stage III (above and below diaphragm)</li>
                        <li><strong>Treatment Status:</strong> Active surveillance (watch and wait)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="content-section">
                    <h4>Complete Diagnostic Workup</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Core needle biopsy (July 2024): CLL/SLL confirmed</li>
                        <li>Flow cytometry: 90% clonal B-cells with characteristic immunophenotype</li>
                        <li>PET CT (August 2024): Low-level uptake above and below diaphragm</li>
                        <li>FISH studies (November 2024): ATM deletion, 13q14.2 deletion</li>
                        <li>IGVH status: Non-mutated</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="content-section">
                <h3>Recent Clinical Status (August 2025)</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Patient feeling well, no B symptoms</li>
                    <li>Independent in activities of daily living</li>
                    <li>Active - driving, managing properties, refinishing furniture</li>
                    <li>Physical exam: ~2cm left cervical lymph node palpable</li>
                    <li>Labs: WBC 7.34, Absolute lymphocyte count 3.48</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="success-box">
                <h3>Follow-up Plan Documented</h3>
                <p><strong>"Return to clinic in 3 months with repeat CBC, CMP, LDH"</strong></p>
                <p>Next appointment was due: <strong>November 2025</strong> (when patient presented to hospital)</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 11: Flow Cytometry Results -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Diagnostic Pathology (July 2024)</h1>
            
            <div class="content-section">
                <h3>Flow Cytometry - Right Cervical Lymph Node Biopsy</h3>
                
                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4>Cell Population</h4>
                    <p style="font-size: 1.2em;"><strong>90% of lymphocytes are clonal B-cells</strong></p>
                </div>

                <table>
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Marker</th>
                            <th>Result</th>
                            <th>Significance</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td>CD19</td>
                            <td class="checkmark">Positive</td>
                            <td>B-cell marker</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>CD5</td>
                            <td class="checkmark">Positive</td>
                            <td>T-cell marker - ABNORMAL for B-cells</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>CD23</td>
                            <td class="checkmark">Partial</td>
                            <td>Typically positive in CLL</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Surface Immunoglobulin</td>
                            <td>Dim lambda</td>
                            <td>Monoclonal (clonal restriction)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>CD10</td>
                            <td class="crossmark">Negative</td>
                            <td>Rules out follicular lymphoma</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>FMC7</td>
                            <td class="crossmark">Negative</td>
                            <td>Typical for CLL</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>CD38</td>
                            <td>19-30%</td>
                            <td>Prognostic marker</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td>Kappa:Lambda ratio</td>
                            <td class="lab-high">0.01</td>
                            <td>Markedly restricted (normal ~2:1)</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </div>

            <div class="critical-box" style="margin-top: 30px;">
                <h3>Pathology Interpretation</h3>
                <p style="font-size: 1.3em; font-weight: bold;">
                    This immunophenotype is DIAGNOSTIC for Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia (CLL)
                </p>
                <p style="margin-top: 15px;">
                    The combination of CD19+, CD5+, CD23+, dim surface immunoglobulin, and monoclonal 
                    light chain restriction is pathognomonic for CLL/SLL.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="learning-point">
                <h3>Key Diagnostic Criteria (IWCLL 2018)</h3>
                <p><strong>CLL/SLL Requires:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>≥5,000/µL clonal B-lymphocytes × 3 months, OR</li>
                    <li>ANY count with lymphadenopathy or organomegaly</li>
                    <li>PLUS characteristic flow cytometry findings</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>This patient met all criteria.</strong></p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 12: Prior Imaging -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Prior Imaging Findings</h1>
            
            <div class="timeline">
                <div class="timeline-item">
                    <div class="timeline-date">CT Chest (8 Months Prior to Admission)</div>
                    <h4>Key Findings:</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Multiple enlarged lymph nodes:
                            <ul>
                                <li>Axillary (bilateral)</li>
                                <li>Mediastinal</li>
                                <li>Upper abdomen</li>
                            </ul>
                        </li>
                        <li>Rib fractures (left 7th-8th, old right 9th)</li>
                        <li>T11 compression deformity</li>
                        <li>6mm RUL nodule (stable)</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p style="margin-top: 15px; font-weight: bold;">
                        Pattern documented as: "Consistent with known lymphoproliferative disorder"
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="timeline-item">
                    <div class="timeline-date">PET CT (4 Months Before Admission)</div>
                    <h4>Key Findings:</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Low-level FDG uptake above and below the diaphragm</li>
                        <li>Multiple lymph nodes with metabolic activity</li>
                        <li>No evidence of high-grade transformation</li>
                        <li>No splenomegaly</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p style="margin-top: 15px; font-weight: bold;">
                        Stage: Lugano Stage III (above and below diaphragm)
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="critical-box" style="margin-top: 30px;">
                <h3>Critical Recognition</h3>
                <p style="font-size: 1.2em;">
                    The lymphadenopathy seen on the current CT scan was <strong>NOT new</strong>. 
                    It had been documented 8 months prior and was consistent with the patient's known 
                    diagnosis of SLL/CLL.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="highlight-box">
                <h3>Clinical Implication</h3>
                <p>
                    <strong>Chronic vs. Acute findings completely change management approach.</strong>
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Chronic lymphadenopathy → Known diagnosis, no new workup needed</li>
                    <li>New lymphadenopathy → Requires diagnostic evaluation</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 15px;">
                    Comparing current imaging to prior studies is essential to avoid unnecessary workup.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 13: The Opportunity for Learning -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Reflection: Opportunities for Enhanced Care</h1>
            
            <div class="learning-point">
                <h3>What We Can Learn From This Case</h3>
                <p style="font-size: 1.1em; margin-bottom: 20px;">
                    This case provides valuable insights into how we can improve our diagnostic processes 
                    and care coordination.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="two-column">
                <div class="content-section">
                    <h3>Initial Assessment</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Patient presented with recurrent pneumonia</li>
                        <li>CT scan showed lymphadenopathy</li>
                        <li>Plan was to pursue diagnostic workup</li>
                        <li>Treatment focused on acute infection</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="content-section">
                    <h3>Additional Context Available</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Established SLL/CLL diagnosis (16 months prior)</li>
                        <li>Active hematology/oncology care</li>
                        <li>Chronic lymphadenopathy documented</li>
                        <li>Immunocompromised status</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top: 30px;">
                <h3>Contributing Factors to Consider</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Patient-level:</strong> Progressive dementia limiting reliable history</li>
                    <li><strong>Documentation:</strong> Diagnosis not prominently displayed in problem list</li>
                    <li><strong>Workflow:</strong> Time constraints on admission may limit comprehensive review</li>
                    <li><strong>System:</strong> Information spanning multiple encounters and specialists</li>
                    <li><strong>Communication:</strong> Care coordination between hospitalist and subspecialists</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="learning-point">
                <h3>Systems-Based Perspective</h3>
                <p>
                    This case illustrates how multiple factors can contribute to gaps in information transfer. 
                    Understanding these factors helps us design better systems rather than focusing on 
                    individual performance.
                </p>
            </div>

            <div class="emphasis">
                Our goal: Learn from this experience to improve care for future patients
            </div>
        </div>

